# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bakunawa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The lustrous fiber is traditionally hand-loomed into various indigenous textiles (**abaca cloth** or **medriñaque**) in the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They are still featured prominently as the traditional material of the barong tagalog, the national male attire of the Philippines, as well as in sheer lace-like fabrics called *nipis* used in various clothing components.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Native abaca textiles also survive into the modern era among various ethnic groups, like the *t'nalak* of the T'boli people and the *dagmay* of the Bagobo people.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abaca is also used in traditional Philippine millinery, as well as for bags, shawls, and other decorative items.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The hatmaking straw made from Manila hemp is called *tagal* or *tagal straw*.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The fiber is also exceptionally strong, stronger than hemp and naturally salt-resistant, making it ideal for making twines and ropes (especially for maritime shipping).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] It became a major trade commodity in the colonial era for this reason.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The abaca industry declined sharply in the mid-20th century when abaca plantations were decimated by World War II and plant diseases, as well as the invention of nylon in the 1930s.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Today, abaca is mostly used in a variety of specialized paper products including tea bags, filter paper and banknotes.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila envelopes and Manila paper derive their name from this fiber.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abaca is classified as a hard fiber, along with coir, henequin and sisal.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abaca is grown as a commercial crop in the Philippines, Ecuador, and Costa Rica.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The abacá plant is stoloniferous, meaning that the plant produces runners or shoots along the ground that then root at each segment.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Cutting and transplanting rooted runners is the primary technique for creating new plants, since seed growth is substantially slower.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá has a "false trunk" or pseudostem about 6–15 inches (15–38 cm) in diameter.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The leaf stalks (petioles) are expanded at the base to form sheaths that are tightly wrapped together to form the pseudostem.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] There are from 12 to 25 leaves, dark green on the top and pale green on the underside, sometimes with large brown patches.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They are oblong in shape with a deltoid base.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The petioles grow to at least 1 foot (30 cm) in length.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] When the plant is mature, the flower stalk grows up inside the pseudostem.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The male flower has five petals, each about 1.5 inches (3.8 cm) long.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The leaf sheaths contain the valuable fiber.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] After harvesting, the coarse fibers range in length from 6–12 feet (180–370 cm) long.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They are composed primarily of cellulose, lignin, and pectin.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The fruit, which is inedible and is rarely seen as harvesting occurs before the plant fruits, grows to about 2–3 inches (5.1–7.6 cm) in length and 1 inch (2.5 cm) in diameter.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] It has black turbinate seeds that are 0.167 inches (0.42 cm) in diameter.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The abacá plant belongs to the banana family, Musaceae; it resembles the closely related wild seeded bananas, *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Within the genus *Musa*, it is placed in section *Callimusa* (now including the former section *Australimusa*), members of which have a diploid chromosome number of 2n= 20.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The Philippines, especially the Bicol region in Luzon, has the most abaca genotypes and cultivars.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Genetic analysis using simple sequence repeats (SSR) markers revealed that the Philippines' abaca germplasm is genetically diverse.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abaca genotypes in Luzon had higher genetic diversity than Visayas and Mindanao.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Ninety-five (95) percent was attributed to molecular variance within the population, and only 5% of the molecular variance to variation among populations.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Genetic analysis by Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Mean (UPGMA) revealed several clusters irrespective of geographical origin.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Before synthetic textiles came into use, *M. textilis* was a major source of high quality fiber: soft, silky and fine.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Ancestors of the modern abacá are thought to have originated from the eastern Philippines, where there is significant rainfall throughout the year.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Wild varieties of abacá can still be found in the interior forests of the island province of Catanduanes, away from cultivated areas.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Today, Catanduanes has many other modern kinds of abacá which are more competitive.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] For many years, breeders from various research institutions have made the cultivated varieties of Catanduanes even more competitive in local and international markets.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] This results in the optimum production of the island which had a consistent highest production throughout the archipelago.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Europeans first came into contact with Abacá fibre when Ferdinand Magellan landed in the Philippines in 1521, as the natives were already cultivating it and utilizing it in bulk for textiles.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Throughout the Spanish colonial era, it was referred to as "*medriñaque*" cloth.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] By 1897, the Philippines were exporting almost 100,000 tons of abacá, and it was one of the three biggest cash crops, along with tobacco and sugar.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] In fact, from 1850 through the end of the 19th century, sugar or abacá alternated with each other as the biggest export crop of the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] This 19th-century trade was predominantly with the United States and the making of ropes was done mainly in New England, although in time rope-making shifted back to the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] From 1898 to 1946, the United States colonized the Philippines following the Spanish–American War.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] In the early 1900s, a train running from Danao to Argao would transport Philippine abacá from the plantations to Cebu City for export.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The railway system was destroyed during World War II; the abaca continues to be transported to Cebu by road.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Outside the Philippines, abacá was first cultivated on a large scale in Sumatra in 1925 under the Dutch, who had observed its cultivation in the Philippines for cordage since the nineteenth century, followed up by plantings in Central America in 1929 sponsored by the U.S.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] It also was transplanted into India and Guam.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Commercial planting began in 1930 in British North Borneo; at the onset of World War II, the supply from the Philippines was eliminated by the Empire of Japan.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Department of Agriculture started production in Panama, Costa Rica, Honduras, and Guatemala.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Today, abacá is produced primarily in the Philippines and Ecuador.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The Philippines produces between 85% and 95% of the world's abacá, and the production employs 1.5 million people.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Production has declined because of virus diseases.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The plant is normally grown in well-drained loamy soil, using rhizomes planted at the start of the rainy season.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] In addition, new plants can be started by seeds.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Growers harvest abacá fields every three to eight months after an initial growth period of 12–25 months.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Harvesting is done by removing the leaf-stems after flowering but before the fruit appears.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The plant loses productivity between 15 and 40 years.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The slopes of volcanoes provide a preferred growing environment.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] When the processing is complete, the bundles of fiber are pale and lustrous with a length of 6–12 feet (1.8–3.7 m).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] In Costa Rica, more modern harvest and drying techniques are being developed to accommodate the very high yields obtained there.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] According to the Philippine Fiber Industry Development Authority, the Philippines provided 87.4% of the world's abacá in 2014, earning the Philippines US$111.33 million.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The demand is still greater than the supply.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The remainder came from Ecuador (12.5%) and Costa Rica (0.1%).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The Bicol region in the Philippines produced 27,885 metric tons of abacá in 2014, the largest of any Philippine region.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The Philippine Rural Development Program (PRDP) and the Department of Agriculture reported that in 2009–2013, Bicol Region had a 39% share of Philippine abacá production of which an overwhelming 92% came from Catanduanes Island.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Eastern Visayas, the second largest producer had 24% and the Davao Region, the third largest producer had 11% of the total production.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Around 42 percent of the total abacá fiber shipments from the Philippines went to the United Kingdom in 2014, making it the top importer.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Germany imported 37.1 percent abacá pulp from the Philippines, importing around 7,755 metric tons (MT).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Sales of abacá cordage surged 20 percent in 2014 to a total of 5,093MT from 4,240MT, with the United States holding around 68 percent of the market.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá is vulnerable to a number of pathogens, notably abaca bunchy top virus, abaca bract mosaic virus, and abaca mosaic virus.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Due to its strength, it is a sought after product and is the strongest of the natural fibers.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] It is used by the paper industry for such specialty uses such as tea bags, banknotes and decorative papers.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] It can be used to make handcrafts such as hats, bags, carpets, clothing and furniture.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá fibers were traditionally woven into sturdy textiles and clothing in the Philippines since pre-colonial times.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Along with cotton, they were the main source of textile fibers used for clothing in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá cloth was often compared to calico in terms of texture and was a major trade commodity in the pre-colonial maritime trade and the Spanish colonial era.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] There are multiple traditional types and names of abaca cloth among the different ethnic groups of the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Undyed plain abacá cloth, woven from fine fibers of abaca, is generally known as *sinamáy* in most of the islands.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá cloth with a more delicate texture is called *tinampipi*.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] While especially fine lace-like abacá cloth is called *nipis* or *lupis*.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Fine abacá fibers may also be woven with *piña*, silk, or fine cotton to create a fabric called *jusi*.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Traditional abacá textiles were often dyed in various colors from various natural dyes.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] These include blue from indigo (*tarum*, *dagum*, *tayum*, etc.); black from ebony (*knalum* or *batulinao*) leaves; red from noni roots and *sapang*; yellow from turmeric (*kalawag*, *kuning*, etc.); and so on.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They were often woven into specific patterns, and further ornamented with embroidery, beadwork, and other decorations.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Most clothing made from abacá took the form of the *baro* (also *barú* or *bayú*, literally "shirt" or "clothing"), a simple collar-less shirt or jacket with close-fitting long sleeves worn by both men and women in most ethnic groups in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] These were paired with wraparound sarong-like skirts (for both men and women), close-fitting pants, or loincloths (*bahag*).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] During the Spanish colonial era, abacá cloth became known as **medriñaque** in Spanish (apparently derived from a native Cebuano name).
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They were exported to other Spanish colonies since the 16th century.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] A waistcoat of a native Quechua man in Peru was recorded as being made of medriñaque as early as 1584.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá cloth also appear in English records, spelled variously as **medrinacks**, **medrianacks**, **medrianackes**, and **medrinacles**, among other names.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] They were used as canvas for sails and for stiffening clothing like skirts, collars, and doublets.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Philippine indigenous tribes still weave abacá-based textiles like *t'nalak*, made by the Tiboli tribe of South Cotabato, and *dagmay*, made by the Bagobo people.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá cloth is found in museum collections around the world, like the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and the Textile Museum of Canada.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] The inner fibers are also used in the making of hats, including the "Manila hats", slippers, hammocks, matting, cordage, ropes, coarse twines, and types of canvas.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila rope is a type of rope made from manila hemp.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila rope is very durable, flexible, and resistant to salt water damage, allowing its use in rope, hawsers, ships' lines, and fishing nets.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] A 1 inch (2.5 cm) rope can require 4 metric tons (8,800 lb) to break.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila rope is still the only material specified for lifeboat falls (the ropes with which a ship's lifeboat is lowered) in the United Kingdom.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila ropes shrink when they become wet.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] This effect can be advantageous under certain circumstances, but if it is not a wanted feature, it should be well taken into account.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Since shrinkage is more pronounced the first time the rope becomes wet, new rope is usually immersed into water and put to dry before use so that the shrinkage is less than it would be if the rope had never been wet.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] A major disadvantage in this shrinkage is that many knots made with manila rope became harder and more difficult to untie when wet, thus becoming subject of increased stress.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila rope will rot after a period of time when exposed to saltwater.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Manila hemp rope was previously the favoured variety of rope used for executions by hanging, both in the U.K. and USA.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Usually 3⁄4 to 1 inch (19 to 25 mm) diameter, boiled prior to use to take out any overelasticity.
[src:bakunawa/abaca] Abacá fiber was once used primarily for rope, but this application is now of minor significance.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] In the Philippine occult tradition, there is usually a corresponding agimat to deal with in a particular area in a person's life.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] The most frequent types of agimat are used for removing hexes and exorcism of evil spirits.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] An agimat, also called a *gayuma*, serves as a love charm which makes the owner more attractive to the opposite sex.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] An agimat is usually accompanied by a small book of magic incantations which must be read during Good Friday or a certain special date to attain the amulet's full power and benefit.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] An agimat could also be in the form of clothing with magic words inscribed on it, or even in the form of edible enchanted mud (*putik* in Tagalog).
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Other methods of obtaining an agimat is by getting the liquid that is drained from an exhumed body of an unbaptized child or aborted fetus or offering food and drink to the spirits in a cemetery at midnight on Holy Wednesday or Holy Thursday.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Most of the amulets bear Latin inscriptions.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Like those in Quiapo district in Manila, most of the agimat merchants are near churches (such as in its courtyard or in the marketplace nearby).
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Filipino freedom fighters also wore *anting-anting* to battle against the Spaniards and the Americans.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Filipino hero Macario Sakay wore a vest that has religious images and Latin phrases to protect him from bullets.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Former President of the Philippines Ferdinand Marcos, claimed that he was allegedly given an anting-anting by Gregorio Aglipay that could supposedly make Marcos invisible.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Marcos said that the agimat is a sliver of wood that was inserted into his back before the Bataan campaign on 1942.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Earliest reports of anting-anting are from the records of Spanish priests in the early colonial period.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] Pardo de Tavera defines the anting-anting as *amuleto que salva la vida, da poder sobre natural* ("an amulet, of super natural power, that saves lives").
[src:bakunawa/agimat] With the Christianization of the Philippines, anting-anting appropriated the forms of the new religion, and incorporated as well the esoteric symbols of Freemasonry.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] An Islamic version of anting-anting exists in the Southern Muslim islands.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] In Filipino films, the wearer of the *agimat* gains superhuman strength, invisibility, heightened senses, self-healing, and elemental powers.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] With it, the person can also be able to shoot or fire lightning via hands, or generate electricity throughout one's body.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] The person can also perform telekinesis, stop a live bullet, can have premonitions, flight, morphing abilities, camouflage abilities like a chameleon, can have extreme good luck, possess invincibility, or perform miracle curative powers.
[src:bakunawa/agimat] In his Filipino films, actor Ramon Revilla, Sr., as *Nardong Putik* has an anting-anting that renders him invulnerable.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] The series is streaming online on YouTube.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] The first season was directed by Jeffrey John Imutan and features the voices of Pen Medina, Mike Tan, Louise delos Reyes, Tonipet Gaba, Betong Sumaya, Kylie Padilla, Pekto, John Feir, Glaiza de Castro, Gabby Eigenmann, Jeric Gonzales, Bea Binene and Roi Vinzon.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] In February 2016, it was announced that it would return for a second season.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] Jeffrey John Imutan returned as director.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] Season two's voice actors included Leo Martinez, RJ Padilla, Bianca Umali, Love Añover, Miggs Cuaderno, John Feir, LJ Reyes, Benjamin Alves, Frencheska Farr, Rafa Siguion-Reyna, Tonipet Gaba, and Zymic Jaranilla.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] According to AGB Nielsen Philippines' Mega Manila household television ratings, the pilot episode of *Alamat* earned a 16.2% rating.
[src:bakunawa/alamat-tv-program] The final episode scored a 15.4% rating.
[src:bakunawa/alan-legendary-creature] The **Alan** are deformed spirits from the folklore of the Tinguian tribe of the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/alan-legendary-creature] They have wings and can fly, and their fingers and toes point backwards.
[src:bakunawa/alan-legendary-creature] The *Alan* are said to take drops of menstrual blood, miscarried fetuses, afterbirth, or other reproductive waste and transform them into human children, whom they then raise as their own.
[src:bakunawa/alan-legendary-creature] They live near springs in extremely fine houses, made of gold and other valuables.
[src:bakunawa/amalanhig] The *Amalanhig* are depicted as externally identical to humans, though there is an enlargement of the upper canines in most individuals.
[src:bakunawa/amalanhig] The *Amalanhig* is a variant of the vampire native to the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Amaya, born in the reign of Rajah Mangubat and as the daughter Datu Bugna, she is a "binukot" - a hidden princess and can't step on ground.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Born with a twin snake, a secret hidden by her father to keep her away from danger.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Due to having a twin snake, her destiny is to become the savior of her land against Rajah Mangubat.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] In September 2011, Aljur Abrenica, Ronnie Lazaro and Yasmien Kurdi joined the series.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Principal photography commenced in March 2011.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] The series was extended until January 13, 2012.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Before the series started, a one-hour primer titled *Amaya: The Making of An Epic* was aired on May 28, 2011.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] The show was hosted by Cesar Montano and Miguel Tanfelix, it presented behind the scenes of *Amaya* from the brainstorming of the management including interviews from Jun Lana and Doctolero, the creative minds behind the story with the guidance of historians from the University of the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] According to AGB Nielsen Philippines' Mega Manila household television ratings, the pilot episode of *Amaya* earned a 26.2% rating.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] The final episode scored a 32.7% rating.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Amaya is promoted by the National Historical Commission of the Philippines and Department of Education due to its cultural concept that shows and depicts the Filipino material culture, beliefs, traditions and mores in the Pre-Hispanic era.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] It also teaches the history of the Philippines by means of epics and legends passed as oral literature through generations.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] The show's creators relied heavily on classic Philippine history reference materials such as the Boxer Codex, an early pictographic account of Filipino culture and physical appearances around the time the Spaniards began colonizing the islands.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Historical references include the names of the characters in the series, such as Alunsina, from the epics Hinilawod and the Labaw Donggon.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Amaya was recognized by the Meycauayan Jewelry Industry Association, Inc., an organization composed of 135 jewellers in Meycauayan, Bulacan, for the promotion of the country's rich jewelry-making heritage.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Apart from Filipino customs and traditions, the series also features native costumes and jewelry patterned after the popular designs of the era.
[src:bakunawa/amaya-tv-series] Most of the jewelries in the series were crafted by jewellers from Meycauayan, Bulacan.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Games in which a ball is hit or thrown have been referenced as far back as Homer and ancient Egypt.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A game similar to handball was played by Northern and Central Americans from 1500 BC, most famously by the Aztecs as the Mesoamerican ballgame, but no references to a rebound game using a wall survive.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] It is thought that these ancient games more closely resembled a form of hand tennis.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Further examples of similar games include the European-originated games of *Basque pelota* (or *Jai-alai*), Gaelic handball, *Valencian frontó*, International fronton and Eton fives.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] References to similar games (then referred to as either "hand-tennis" and "hand-ball") have been found as early as 1287, when the Synod of Exeter banned the game due to the damage it caused to church buildings.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Other notable examples of wall ball games being banned include Robert Braybrooke, Bishop of London, who in 1385 prohibited the game.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Another recorded game of striking a ball against a wall using a hand was in Scotland in 1427, when King James I ordered a cellar window in his palace courtyard to be blocked up, as it was interfering with his game.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In Ireland, the earliest written record of a similar game is in the 1527 town statutes of Galway, which forbade the playing of ball games against the walls of the town.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The first depiction of an Irish form of handball does not appear until 1785.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The sport of handball in Ireland was eventually standardized as Gaelic handball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] By the mid-19th century, Australians were playing a similar game, which developed into the modern sport of Australian handball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In *Treacherous Beauty*, by Mark Jacob and Stephen H.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Case, about the Arnold-Andre conspiracy, Major John André and General Sir Henry Clinton are said to have played a game called handball during the American Revolution.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The earliest record of the modern game in the United States mentions two handball courts in San Francisco in 1873.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The sport grew over the next few decades.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] By the early 1900s, four-wall handball was well established and a one-wall game was developed in New York City by beach-goers who hit bald tennis balls with their hands against the sides of the wooden jetties that lined beaches.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] This led to a rise in one-wall handball at New York beaches and by the 1930s, thousands of indoor and outdoor one-wall courts had been built throughout the city.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] American handball is seen predominantly in parks, beaches, and high school yards in New York City, Lynbrook, New York, Philadelphia, Chicago and other large urban areas.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] National championships in handball have been held annually in the United States since 1919.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] These championships were organized by the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU) until 1950, when their control was transferred to the newly formed United States Handball Association (USHA).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] For a complete list of champions, see List of American Handball Champions in the United States, and List of American Handball Women's Champions in the United States.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The sports of racquetball, squash, fives, four-wall and one-wall paddleball were heavily influenced by handball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Four-wall and one-wall paddleball were created when people took up wooden paddles to play on handball courts.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Four-wall paddleball was invented in 1930 by Earl Riskey, a physical-education instructor at the University of Michigan, when he came up with the idea of using paddles to play on the school's handball courts.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Racquetball was invented in 1949 by Joseph Sobek in Greenwich, Connecticut, when he played handball using a strung racquet.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] American handball is played on a walled court, with either a single (front) wall, three walls, or in a fully enclosed four-wall court; four-wall courts typically have a ceiling while three-wall courts may or may not.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The four-wall court is a rectangular box.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The front wall is 20 feet (6.1 m) square, and the side walls are 40 feet (12.2 m) long and 20 feet (6.1 m) high.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In the middle of the floor lies a short line, dividing the floor into two 20 feet (6.1 m) squares.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Also along the floor is the service line, which is 5 feet (1.5 m) in front of the short line.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The service zone is the area between these two lines.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The back wall of the court is usually 12 feet (3.7 m) high, with an above gallery for the referee, scorekeeper and spectators.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Some courts have a glass back wall and glass side walls to allow for better viewing.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In three-wall court handball, the court often has a front wall and two full side walls, or the front wall is flanked by two triangular wings.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Handball may be played as singles (two players against each other), doubles (two teams of two players), or "cutthroat" (three players rotating one against two).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In cutthroat handball, one server plays against two receivers, until they are "put out" (other terms include "down" or "side out").
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Serves rotate in this way until one player wins by scoring either 7, 11, 15, or 21 points.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Should both teams reach a score 1 below the winning score, the game can be continued by "win-by-two" or "straight".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In "win-by-two", the winning score is increased by 2 points.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In 'straight', the score remains the same and cannot be pushed.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] When a tie of 20 is reached in a 21-point match, a common decision is 'straight 25', where the winning score is set to 25 and cannot be changed.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The cutthroat mode of play is also known as "triangles".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The ball is served by one player standing in the service zone.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The server begins by dropping the ball to the floor of the service zone and striking it, after one bounce, with the hand or fist so that it hits the front wall.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The ball must hit the front wall first and it may then hit at most one side wall before the first bounce.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The served ball must then bounce on the floor past the short line but before reaching the back wall.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] If the served ball lands in front of the short line, it is called a "short", while a serve that reaches the back wall without bouncing is called "long", and a serve that hits both side walls before hitting the floor is called a "3-wall".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] These are all types of errors known as service faults.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] After one service fault, the server will have only one serve remaining.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The server is "put out" by hitting two faults in a row and becomes the receiver, but if any serve hits the ceiling, floor, or a side wall *before* hitting the front wall, the server is out (no second serve allowed).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In doubles, the server's teammate has to stand in the service area with their back to a side wall in a service box, marked by a parallel line 18 inches (46 cm) from the side wall, until the ball passes the short line.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] While the server has the ball, the receiver must stand at least 5 feet (1.5 m) behind the short line, indicated by dashed lines extending 6 inches (15 cm) from each side wall.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Once the ball is served, the receiver must hit the ball either directly ("on the fly") or after the first bounce.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A receiver choosing to take the serve on the fly, however, must first wait for the ball to cross the short line (the dashed line, in racquetball).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The ball can bounce off the floor twice.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Also, any player during a return may hit the ball off the floor before it touches the front wall.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The server then hits the ball on the rebound from the front wall, and play continues with the opponents alternately hitting the ball until one of them fails to make a legal return.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] After the serve and return, the ball may be played from anywhere and may hit any number of walls, the ceiling, or a player so long as it hits the front wall before bouncing on the floor.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Players can "hinder" (block) their opponents from hitting the ball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Servers failing to make a legal return is "put out" and becomes the receiver.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] If the receiver fails to make the return, a point goes to the server, who continues to serve until "put out".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Only the server/serving team can score points.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The game goes to the player/team first to score 21 points.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A match goes to the player/team to win two out of three games; the third game goes to 11 points.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A three-wall handball court is an outside court with a front-wall, two side-walls (these may be "full" or "half"—half being a pair of sloping side-walls), and no back-wall in the play area.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] It is played very much like an indoor four-wall court, only with the challenge of returning the ball without any back-wall rebound.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The long line at the forty-foot mark is considered out if the ball hits it when hitting the floor.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] One-wall handball courts have a wall 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 16 feet (4.9 m) high.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The court floor is 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 34 feet (10.4 m) long.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] When not played as part of tournament or league play, the one-wall game typically uses the bigger ball called "the big blue".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The main difference between one-wall handball and other versions is that the ball must always be played off the front wall.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] One-wall handball can be watched by more people than a four-wall game.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The court is also cheaper to build, making this version of handball popular at gymnasiums and playgrounds.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] In New York City alone, an estimated 2,299 public handball courts occupy the five boroughs.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A typical outfit includes protective gloves, sneakers, athletic shorts and goggles.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Eye protection is required in tournament handball, as the ball moves at high speeds and in close proximity to the players.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] It is rarely used in "street" handball, however, where a softer "big blue" ball is usually used.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The black or blue rubber ball weighs 2.3 ounces (65 g) and is 1.875 inches (4.76 cm) in diameter (smaller, heavier, and more dense than a racquetball), is hit with a gloved hand (open palm, fingers, fist, back of hand) (informal games often do not include gloves).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A true handball is referred to as an "ace ball" or, in earlier days, "blackball".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A racquetball used to play handball is called a "big ball" or "big blue".
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A small ball is hard, bounces higher and moves faster.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Types of small balls include the Red Ace (for men) and the White Ace (for women).
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] The Red Ace small ball is heavier than the White Ace small ball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] A big ball bounces slower and is softer and hollower than a small ball.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Four-wall games use the small ball almost exclusively.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Three-wall and one-wall games use both balls.
[src:bakunawa/american-handball] Both balls are used extensively in New York City, with formal tournaments for big ball, one example being NYC Big Blue.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The **Bakunawa**, also called the **Philippine moon-eating dragon**, the **Philippine moon dragon**, **moon dragon**, or the **moon-eating dragon**, is a dragon-like serpent in Philippine mythology.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It is believed to be the cause of eclipses, earthquakes, rains, and wind.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The movements of the Bakunawa served as a geomantic calendar system for ancient Filipinos and were part of the rituals of the *babaylan* priestess.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It is usually depicted with a characteristic looped tail and a single horn on the nose.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It was believed to inhabit either the sky or the underworld.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Due to increasing trade contacts with South Asia and the Indianization of Southeast Asia, the Bakunawa later became syncretized with the Nāga, Rahu, and Ketu of Hindu-Buddhist mythology.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Bakunawa is believed to be originally a compound word meaning "bent snake", from Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian **ba(ŋ)kuq* ("bent", "curved") and **sawa* ("large snake", "python").
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Spelling variants include **Vakonawa**, **Baconaua**, or **Bakonaua**.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] When the moon is eclipsed, the Indians of various districts generally go out into the street or into the open fields, with bells, panastanes, etc.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] They strike them with great force and violence in order that they might thereby protect the moon which they say is being eaten or swallowed by the dragon, tiger, or crocodile.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa is also sometimes known as **Naga**, from syncretization with the Hindu-Buddhist serpent deity, Nāga.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It was also syncretized with the Hindu-Buddhist navagraha pair, Rahu and Ketu, deities who were responsible for eclipses of the sun and moon, respectively.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Versions of the Bakunawa also existed in other myths in the Philippines, sharing the common theme of being the cause of eclipses.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The most similar to the Bakunawa is the Tagalog **Laho** (derived from Rahu; also known as Nono or Buaya), a serpent-like dragon that causes moon eclipses.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In Kapampangan mythology, **Láwû** is depicted as a bird-like dragon or serpent that causes both solar and lunar eclipses, however, its features are closer to the demon Rahu.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Both the words *laho* and *láwû* mean "eclipse" (also in modern parlance "to disappear" or "to vanish") in the Tagalog and Kapampangan language.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Other mythical creatures related to the Bakunawa include the Hiligaynon Bawa, Bauta, or Olimaw; the Mandaya and Manobo Tambanakua; the Bagobo Minokawa; and the Maranao Arimaonga.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] However, these do not always appear serpent-like.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Maranao Arimaonga for example, is depicted as a lion-like dragon; while the Hiligaynon Olimaw is a winged serpent; the Bagobo Minokawa is a dragon-like giant bird; and the Mandaya Tambanokano and Manobo Tambanakua is a giant crab (sometimes also a giant tarantula or scorpion).
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] According to tales, the Bakunawa is believed to be the cause of eclipses.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] During ancient times, pre-colonial Cebuanos believed that their supreme god—Bathala, or Kaptan the Visayan tradition—created 7 moons to illuminate the night sky.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa, amazed by their beauty, would rise from the ocean and swallow the moons whole, angering Bathala and causing them to be mortal enemies.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] To prevent the complete devouring of the moons, early Filipinos would rush outdoors, clanging pots and pans to startle the Bakunawa into disgorging the moons.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In some accounts, musical instruments were used to produce soothing sounds intended to lull the creature into sleep, allowing brave villagers an opportunity to drive it away.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa is traditionally described not only as a “moon eater” but also as a fearsome being known to consume humans.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa is said to have a sister in the form of a sea turtle.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] This turtle would reportedly travel to an island in the Philippines to lay its eggs.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] However, locals observed that each time the turtle came ashore, the surrounding waters encroached further inland, reducing the island's size.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Fearing the eventual loss of their land, the locals killed the turtle.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Upon learning of its sister’s death, the Bakunawa emerged from the sea and consumed the moon.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In response, the people sought intervention from a supreme deity, who declined to punish the creature directly but instructed the people to create loud noises by striking pots and pans to force the Bakunawa to release the moon.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The story concludes with the moon being expelled and the Bakunawa disappearing.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Another version tells of the Bakunawa falling in love with a human woman from a local tribe.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] When the tribal leader discovered their relationship, he ordered their dwelling to be destroyed by fire.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Enraged by the loss, the Bakunawa attempted to devour all seven moons as an act of vengeance.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] When it was about to consume the final moon, the deity intervened, punishing the creature by banishing it from the sea.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In this version, eclipses are interpreted as the Bakunawa’s attempts to return to its home and reunite with its lost family.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Some oral traditions describe the Bakunawa as a mobile landmass with communities living on its back.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Within these beliefs, two variants of the creature are distinguished: the flying Bakunawa and the terrestrial, or land-based, Bakunawa.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The story of the *Bakunawa and the Seven Moons* was first documented in Mga Sugilanong Karaan 1913 by Buyser.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It later gained broader recognition when it was included in the 1926 compilation Mga Sugilanong Pilipinhon (Folk Lore Filipino), where Buyser concluded with an account of his personal encounter with beliefs surrounding the Bakunawa.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In this version of the myth, the supreme deity Bathala is said to have created seven moons, each intended to illuminate one night of the week.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] These celestial bodies were believed to bring great beauty and radiance to the night sky.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] However, this celestial harmony was disrupted by the appearance of a colossal serpent-like creature, the Bakunawa, which was said to have coiled itself around the earth.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Drawing comparisons to the apocalyptic serpent described by Saint John in the Apocalipsis, the Bakunawa, driven by envy, consumed six of the moons, leaving only one remaining.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In response, Bathala is said to have planted bamboo on the last moon.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] These markings, visible from Earth, were thought to be the dark patches or "stains" seen on the lunar surface.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Following the loss of six moons, communities took measures to safeguard the final remaining moon from being consumed by the Bakunawa.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] According to the account, widespread panic ensued one night when the Bakunawa reappeared and appeared to attack the moon.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Inhabitants reacted by producing loud noises—striking drums, metal objects, and other instruments—to deter the serpent.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] People reportedly cried out phrases such as “return our moon,” fearing that the loss of the last moon would signal a catastrophic end.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Gathering outside their homes, many knelt in prayer to seek divine intervention.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa was eventually believed to have regurgitated the moon, prompting widespread relief and expressions of gratitude directed toward a higher power.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The joy of the people at the return of the Moon could not be described that night.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] They lifted their hearts to the sky like flowers and uttered their praises of gratefulness to the Almighty who owned all creations.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Despite scientific explanations for lunar eclipses becoming more widely understood, belief in the Bakunawa persisted in some regions.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] In particular, communities in mountainous and coastal areas were said to continue traditional practices—such as creating loud noises—during eclipses, as observed during more recent astronomical events.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] This cultural motif is referenced in the proverb “The footprint of the old people never disappears,” symbolizing the lasting influence of ancestral traditions.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The tale was later reinterpreted by Damiana Eugenio in her anthology Philippine Folk Literature: The Myths, published by the University of the Philippines Press.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] Figures of the Bakunawa's head decorate the hilts of many ancient Filipino swords.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] These swords that originate in Panay are said to bestow upon the *hangaway* or *mandirigma* (sacred warriors) the fearful presence and power of the Bakunawa (or whatever deity/animal they have on their deity hilt) when they wield their swords in combat.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] A children's game called Bulan Bulan, Buwan Buwan, or Bakunawa is played in the Philippines.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] It has 6–8 players arranged in a circle.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] A player acts as the buwan/bulan (moon) while another player acts as the Bakunawa (eclipse), chosen either through Jack-en-poy, *“maalis taya”*, or *“maiba taya.”* The other participants stand in a circle facing the center and holding each other's hands.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The buwan/bulan stands inside the circle, while the Bakunawa stands outside.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The object of the game is for the Bakunawa to tag or touch the *buwan/bulan*.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The rest of the players try to prevent the bakunawa from doing so by holding on to each other and running around the circle as fast as they can while not letting go of the ones next to them.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] For the Bakunawa to get into the circle, he or she asks one of the players, "What chain is this?" and when the player replies, "This is an iron chain," the Bakunawa should ask another player because an iron chain is supposed to be unbreakable.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] A player who wants to let the bakunawa in can say, "This is an abaca chain," and should let go of his or her hold.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] This is usually done when the player playing as the bakunawa is tired from running around.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The *malatikantumanlak* can also try to get in by going under the linked hands.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] If the player chosen as the bakunawa is fast and small enough, this can be done easily.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] As soon as the bakunawa succeeds in getting in, the players forming the circle should let the buwan out of the circle.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] The Bakunawa then tries to break out of the linked hands to try to get out to catch the buwan/bulan.
[src:bakunawa/bakunawa] When the Bakunawa succeeds in catching the buwan/bulan, they exchange places, or if both of them are too tired, another pair from the circle of players is chosen as the new Bakunawa and *buwan/bulan*.
